  <Subject Subject_ID="300264348">
    <Parent_Relationships>
      <Preferred_Parent>
        <Parent_Subject_ID>300056462</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>art genres [300056462], genres in the visual arts [300056444], concepts in the arts and humanities [300056107], Associated Concepts (hierarchy name) [300055126], Associated Concepts Facet [300264086]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Generally, any item created by soldiers, prisoners of war, or civilians from any kind of material, as long as it and they are associated in time or place with armed conflict or its consequences. Specifically, objets of metal, cloth, bone, or wood made as remembrances either during or after World War I or World War II.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000045349/Journal of Material Culture (1996-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Generalmente, cualquier elemento creado por soldados, prisioneros de guerra o civiles, de cualquier tipo de material, en cuanto estén asociados en tiempo o lugar con conflictos armados o sus consecuencias. Específicamente, objetos de metal, tela, hueso o madera realizados como recuerdos tanto durante o después de la I o II Guerra Mundial.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In het algemeen elk voorwerp dat door soldaten, krijgsgevangenen of burgers is gemaakt van ongeacht welk materiaal, mits het voorwerp en de maker in tijd of plaats verbonden zijn met een gewapend conflict of de gevolgen daarvan. In het bijzonder voorwerpen van metaal, stof, been of hout die als aandenken zijn gemaakt tijdens of na de Eerste en de Tweede Wereldoorlog.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052464/Legermuseum</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一般指在任何涉及武裝衝突或其結果的時間或地點，由軍人、戰俘、平民以任何材料創作出來的作品。特別是第一次世界大戰或第二次世界大戰期間或戰後，以金屬、布料、骨頭、木材等等製成如紀念品的物件。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Geralmente, qualquer item criado por soldados, prisioneiros de guerra ou civis a partir de qualquer tipo de material, desde que esteja associado no tempo ou lugar ao conflito armado ou às suas consequências. Especificamente, objetos de metal, tecido, osso ou madeira feitos como lembranças durante ou após a Primeira Guerra Mundial ou a Segunda Guerra Mundial.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
